      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "79a618e6cfdf8d4e",
        "text": "Studies of children's learning (Piaget, 1954) illustrated what might be designated a second level of meaning. Instead of seeking a photographic memory we seek for internal coherence in our systems of meaning. By comparing and contrasting part with part we build up patterns, or systems of categorisation which enable us to see relationships and further explore inconsistencies. Logic, analogy, categorisation, de-construction, humour, metaphor story-telling, myth, are some of the terms which shed light on what we are doing at this level. We are sorting out our meanings in order to see them in relation to one another. This is one requirement of reflective learning and of science."
      },
